–1389":"1361–1389","22 August 1435":"22 August 1435","1461":"1461","1394":"1394","1361":"1361","1392":"1392","1436":"1436","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","1375":"1375","about 1403":"about 1403","1430":"1430","1353":"1353","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1428":"1428","Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"Thame, Oxfordshire, England","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Alderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baldington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Bollington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bollington","meanings":["English: locative name from Bollington (Cheshire)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Baldington was born in 1375, in Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Baldington, was 22 and his mother, Agnes Spencer, was 14. He married Lady Joan Glendale in 1392, in Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at l